WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Leveraging & Contributing to the Pharmaverse for Clinical Trial Reporting in R

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Leveraging & Contributing to the Pharmaverse for Clinical Trial Reporting in R

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.000
That's the title of the workshop I have the pleasure to teach at this year's Posit.com

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
alongside Christina Follmer from GSK and Pavel Lutsky over at Roche.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:22.000
And here's the top three reasons why you should sign up for this workshop.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Reason number one.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Open source is really where all the innovation as it relates to clinical trial reporting is happening.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:34.000
But for the past decades, the industry has exclusively relied on commercial software to report their clinical trials.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:37.000
Over the past five years or so, this has really dramatically changed.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:44.000
And companies, a lot of big pharma companies, small biotechs are all now moving towards using open source tools

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:47.000
and in particular R for their clinical trial reporting.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:51.000
And the Pharmaverse is really where all of this innovation gets integrated

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.000
and you will find a lot of very thoughtfully designed, well-written R packages

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.000
for different aspects of clinical trial reporting.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:02.000
So if you want to be at the cutting edge of the open source development as it relates to clinical trial reporting,

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
this is a workshop you must attend.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:06.000
Number two.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:07.000
Shiny.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:13.000
Well, again, in the past, we have almost exclusively relied on static deliverables such as tables,

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.000
listings and graphs for our final clinical study reports.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
This has been changing in recent years as well.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:27.000
And people increasingly leverage dashboard solutions, interactive data exploration apps for their clinical trial reporting.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Not only internally for more exploratory purposes, but recently also for the regulatory side of things.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
In fact, there has been a pilot submission to the US FDA of a Shiny app

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.000
instead of the more traditional PDF-based static listings, tables and figures.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.000
We are teaching you how to use a particular Shiny framework called Teal,

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.000
where you can learn how to create such an app by yourself.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.000
And I think you will really, really enjoy this experience.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:56.000
And finally, number three, which is you will not only learn how you can leverage these tools,

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.000
but how you can actually actively contribute to them,

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:02.000
such that you can make the tools even better than they already are.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:08.000
If you see something and you think like, hey, we could change this up to make it even better doing XYZ,

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:13.000
we will teach you exactly the steps you need to follow from things like creating issues on GitHub,

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.000
how you can create a feature branch, so on and so forth.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
But also very importantly, how you can contribute if you don't actually want to write our code.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
There's a lot of working groups within the Pharmaverse with different packages,

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:28.000
tackling things like how should we handle lab data as it relates to our Adam datasets.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:31.000
And you can come in there, contribute your expertise,

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:37.000
and that way ensure that what is already, in my opinion, a very, very robust set of packages

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:42.000
becomes even better, more usable for your day-to-day clinical trial reporting work.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
And with that being said, I'm really, really looking forward to seeing you in Chicago.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:48.000
Have a great rest of your day. Cheers.

